question: Has signal-to-knowledge conversion improved since S313 baseline?
method: Programmatic 3-layer audit: table rows (S57-S304 format), pattern bullets (curated synthesis), session sections (S302+ rich format). Classification: canonical (L/P/F/B/ISO/HQ ref) vs file-ref-only vs minimal.
findings: Overall canonical encoding STAGNANT: 42.1% vs 39% baseline (+3.1pp)
Table row canonical encoding 38.1% (+2.1pp from 36%) — within measurement noise
File format shifted: session sections (n=29) added since S302, with 89.7% canonical rate
Pattern bullets grew from 9 to 59 but canonical rate fell from 67% to 47.5%
S313 recommendation 'per-signal L/P prompt' was NOT implemented — no enforcement at signal-write time
Same 2 unresolved signals from S313 still unresolved (S182, S208)

gap_analysis.primary: No enforcement mechanism built: S313 recommended per-signal L/P prompting but this was never wired into any tool
gap_analysis.secondary: Format proliferation without quality: session sections expand signal surface area without increasing canonical encoding
gap_analysis.tertiary: Signal intake slowed 75%: fewer new signals logged per session, suggesting the file is becoming legacy rather than active

structural_diagnosis: L-601 predicts this: voluntary protocol (S313 recommendations) decays to structural floor at creation. Signal conversion needs creation-time enforcement to improve.
verdict: STAGNANT: 42.1% vs 39% baseline. S313 recommendations produced no measurable improvement in 52 sessions. Root cause: no enforcement mechanism built.
